        <div id="collapseThree21" class="collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThree21" data-parent="#accordion">
            <div class="card-body">
                <div class="text-justify">Thiruvannamalai …..Go Matha..... Komatha Pooja and Ayush Homam can be conducted in a private place @ Thiruvannmalai La Woods Hotel Site…..</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify">Sidha’s heavenly paradise and thousands of Sidhargals are alive and they bless the devotees. Successive Kings of South India have given great importance to Tiruvannamalai and the temple of Arunachala. One cannot describe the atmosphere of the temple and the vibration. The variegated architectural styles of generations of kings, who built and renovated its massive gopurams and halls, the living presence of the great saints, who stayed here and sang the Lord’s praise and above all, the infinite compassion and grace of Arunachala, give this holiest of holy places, a timeless quality.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify">THIRUVANNAMALAI is home to Annamalaiyar Temple. Thiruvannamalai has long been associated with many yogis and siddhars. Thiruvannamalai is one of the Pancha Bootha Sthalam representing the fire element. On the day of Karthigai Deepam, a huge lamp is lit at the sunset in a cauldron with three tons of ghee at the top of the Annamalai hill. Every full moon night, thousands of pilgrims worship Lord Shiva by circumambulating the Arunachala hill barefoot. There were many hundreds of saints guru and sidhargal lived in Thiruvannamalai.</div>
<div class="text-justify">By visiting Chidambaram or by being born in Thiruvarur or by dying in Kasi or by merely thinking of Arunachala, you will surely attain Liberation.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify">The supreme knowledge - Self-knowledge, the import of Vedanta, which cannot be attained without great difficulty, but can easily be attained by anyone, who sees the form of this hill from wherever it is visible or who thinks of it by mentally from distance. This Magnetic hill will attract the soul forcibly. What a wonder is this !!! The soul can be saved by thinking of this great Arunagiri, which shines in the mind.</div>
<div class="text-justify">Karthigai Deepam Festival At Tiruvannamalai - Brahma and Vishnu were both quarrelling about their relative superiority. To take a decision and to erase their ego, Lord Shiva stood before them in the form of a blazing mountain. Having failed in their attempt to find out its top and bottom, the two prayed to Lord Shiva for his blessings. He blessed them saying that he would appear in the form of Jothi on top of the hill every year on the day of Karthigai Deepam during the month of Karthigai. To commemorate this event the Deepam festival is being conducted at Thiruvannamalai every year. There is literary evidence to prove that this lamp festival is one of the traditions in Tamil culture. This annual festival attract almost 2 millions visitors to Thiruvannamalai and every one go around (GRIVALAM) the hill of 14 kms by fare foot.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify">Girivalam- the Holy Mountain of Arunachala rises up to an elevation of 2669 feet. The road encircling the mountain, where devotees circumambulate is 14 kms. On Full Moon days and on the day of Karthigai Deepam and on the first day of Tamil New Year, lakhs of devotees undertake girivalam ie., circumambulating the mountain to get the blessings of the Lord Arunachala. This hill is made up of igneous rock connected with fire, which is one of the four kinds of mountains classified by geology. So one can see the truth behind the tradition regarding the origin and formation of this hill. Our religious philosophy is based on science and there is always the combination of Vignana and Meygnana. These two are inextricably intertwined. An American Geologist has stated that Mountain: Arunachala should have been thrown up by the earth under the stress of some violent volcanic eruption in the Dark Ages before even the coal-bearing layers were formed. It existed long before the gigantic saurians of the pre-historic world, moved their ungainly forms through the prehistoric forests that covered our early earth. Arunachala is almost old and as ancient as our planetary home itself. What a miracle !!! Such a barren rock has captivated the souls of sages and saints for ages together. Legends say that Tiruvannamalai was a fire alias Agni Mountain in Krathayuga, Gold alias Swarna Mountain in Thrathayugha, Copper alias Thambra Mountain in Duvaparayuga and Rock Mountain in this Kaliyuga. Arunachala hill has a religious status in our sacred tradition. Tamil legends hold that it is far more ancient than the Himalayas, which are comparatively known to be of later origin. Arunachala is a combination of two Sanskrit words Aruna and Achala. Aruna means 'red' and Achala means ' immovable mount’, thereby known as the "Red Mount".</div>
<div class="text-justify">There are eight Lingas, eight Nandis, more than 350 tanks and many mandapams around the hill. The eight Lingams are Indira Lingams, Agni Lingam, Ema Lingam, Niruthi Lingam, Varuna Lingam, Vaayu Lingam, Kubera Lingam and Esanya Lingam. Caves In The Heart Of Arunachala, Tiruvannamalai - There are many caves in Arunachala Hill. The Puranas say so and even yogis have confirmed, that from these mysterious caves, one can watch the wonderful sights and also watch Siddhars deep in penance, oblivious to the world, content with partaking and absorbing the abundant grace of Arunachala.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify">Siddhars And Saints Of Tiruvannamalai- Many ancient sages from the Himalayas and other sacred places of India came to Arunachala, either on a pilgrimage or to live in its vicinity. Some of these rishis were&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Pulastya, Vasishta, Marichi, Agastya, Dadichi, Nagana, Brigu, Atri, Jabali, Jaimini, Jamadagni, Bharata, Pipalata, Kasyapa, Kumudha, Varsha, Vibandaga, Vyasa, Mandavya, Matanga, Kukshi, Mandakarni, Chandilya, Maduchandas, Gargeya, Apasthamba, Romesamuni, Bhargava, Bharadwaja, Swetaketu, Koundinya, Pundarika, Valmiki, Narada, Vahini, Bodayana, Mrukandu, Durvasa, Gangavarya, Devadatta, Sushruta, Visravas, Mangalya, Rishyasringa, Ekapada, Krouncha, Angiras, Pathanjali, Sanaka, Sanandana, Sanatkumara, Sanatsujata, Maithreya, Pushpajith, Nidaga, Parasara, Vaisampayana, Yajnavalkya, Aswalayana, Anantakaruna, Amalakapriya and Kapila</span></b>. Out of these Valmiki and and a few others gave us the itihasas; Vyasa, Narada and some others gave us the Puranas; Apastamba, Bodayana, Yajnavalkya, Parasara, Jaimini and others gave us portions of the Vedas. Pipalatha and others gave us the Upanishads. All these great sages were attracted by the magnetic power of Arunachala of Tiruvannamalai.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Deiva Sigamani&nbsp;</span></b>Desika Paramacharya Swamigal - 700 years ago, hearing of his greatness, a King came to see him. Just then, his horse was bitten by a snake and the horse died. When the saint heard about the horse, he came out praying to Arunachala, tapped the horse’s body with his cane and brought it back to life. The King inscribed the story of the miracle performed by the saint on the south wall of the third prakara of the temple.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Mangaiyarkarasi</span></b>&nbsp;- She thus gave away all her wealth to Arunachaleswara and attained divine grace on her death. Her generous deeds are lauded in the inscriptions on the walls of the temple prakara.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Pani Pathraswami&nbsp;</span></b>- When he wished to take water to the temple, the water from the Brahma Thirtham came out of its own accord in his hands in the form of a vessel.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Dakshinamurthi Swami -</span></b>&nbsp;While performing many miracles in his life Dakshinamurti Swami, also spread the philosophy of Advaita.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Ammani Ammaiyar&nbsp;</span></b>- She had the gift of curing diseases by giving holy ash. Her samadhi is near the Eesanya linga. A temple has been built over it.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify"><b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Angapradakshinam Annamalai Swami</span></b>&nbsp;- He was thus called because all his life he worshipped Arunachala by performing Angapradakshina that is rolling on the ground in an anticlockwise direction round the hill.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Irai Swamigal</span></b>&nbsp;- It is believed that there are 1008 lingas under each step round the hill, he would recite Arunachala’s name 100 times for each step he took while circumambulating the hill. After doing these for many hours, he would complete going round the hill and continue the chanting 1008 times the next day, from where he had left off.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Guhai Namasivayar</span></b>&nbsp;- Once, Namasivaya happened to bring a dead sheep back to life. Knowing this, some mischievous youths wanted to test him. They put a healthy man on a bamboo pad and had him pretend to be dead and took him to Guhai Namasivaya. Namasivaya, through his powers knew their trick, got annoyed and declared that the man was truly dead. The youths to their concern found that the man on the pad had indeed died. Two of the illustrious disciples of Guhai Namasivaya were Virupakshi Thevar and Guru Namasivayar. The former lived just above the cave of Guhai Namasivayar. At his death, his body naturally reduced to ashes. After about four centuries in the beginning of the 20th century, these ashes were made into the form of a linga by Bhagavan Ramana himself during his stay at Virupakshi cave.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Arunagirinathar</span></b>&nbsp;- Saint Arunagirinathar and Lord Muruga are inseparable. He lost his parents, when he was young and was brought up by his sister living at Tiruvannamalai. He lived a life of pleasure. When his sister scolded him for his conduct, he felt hurt and tried to kill himself by falling from the top of the Vallala Maharaja Gopuram in the temple. Lord Muruga stopped Him and blessed him with spiritual knowledge. Arunagiri spent sometime in Tiruvannamalai meditating on the divine.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Veera Vairagya Murthy Swam</span></b>i - During the Karthigai festival in Tiruvannamalai, he restored to life a cow slaughtered by a Muslim King. He also made the stone Nandi idol of bull to graze on grass. The Muslim King was amazed at his powers and praised the glory of Arunachaleswara.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Sonachala</span></b>&nbsp;- He went round the hill everyday without fail till he reached the Lord’s feet.&nbsp;<b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">Sri Isanya Jnana Desikar Mutt&nbsp;</span></b>&amp; Samadhi Temple - It is said that tigers used to keep guard around this sage when he was absorbed in meditation. He attained Mahasamadhi in 1829. Two tigers sat close to him always. When devotees came to see him, he would ask the tigers to go into the nearby forest. Lord Arunachala used to manifest in the form of a Tiger to guard him.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify"><b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">IDAIKADAR</span></b>&nbsp;- Sri IdaiKadar is one of the 18 renowned siddhars and considered an incarnation of Lord Vishnu. Two of the biggest contributions of IdaiKadar is the invention of Kayakalpa techniques and the arrangement of Navagraha Nine Planets in temples. Kayakalpa is a legendary system of total body rejuvenation. Kayakalpa purifies, nurtures and revitalizes the constituent elements of the body, mind and psyche with a series of customized therapy sessions, herbo-mineral preparations, vital breathing practices, dietary guidelines and daily living recommendations. He is also known to have arranged the positions of the nine planets NavaGraha that are being followed in the temples of India. Earlier in the temples the NavaGrahas were placed circularly i.e. all the nine planets were facing each other and could interact directly. This means that a person going through a rough patch due to the malefic influence of one planet would continue to experience bad time as all the planets are in direct contact with each other and would be passing on their effect to the next one and so on. Realizing this, IdaiKadar arranged the planetary positions in such a way, so that no one planet would face the other planet directly. Idaikadar attained his maha nirvana or salvation in the Agni sthalam – Tiruvannamalai, and it is also believed that, the garbagriha or the main lingam of Tiruvannamalai is built on top of his Jeeva Samadhi. Some people claim that, his Jeeva Samadhi is behind the main lingam on the second orbit of the Lord Arunachaleswarar temple.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify"><b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">SRI RAMANA MAHARSHI,</span></b>&nbsp;Thiruvannamalai - After having attained liberation at the age of 16, Sri Ramana Maharshi left home for Arunachala, a mountain considered sacred by the Hindus, at Tiruvannamalai and lived there for the rest of his life. Sri Ramana maintained that the purest form of his teachings was the powerful silence, which radiated from his presence and calmed the minds of those who were tuned to it.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify"><b><span style="font-family: .SFUIText-Bold;">SATHGURU SESHADIRI SWAMIGAL,&nbsp;</span></b>Thiruvannamalai, one of the greatest saints of all times. He has guided great Gurus like Ramana Maharishi, Vallimalai Sachidananda Swamigal and many others in their spiritual journey. He stayed in the crematoriums at Tiruvannamalai. He took food in the same leaf along with beggars and dogs and never bothered about rain or sunshine and lived with nature. The young child grew into a young sage of infinite realization, disappearing from a locked room where his family tried to keep him bound to family duties, manifesting yet again, his spiritual greatness. He journeyed to the sacred Tiruvannamalai and remained for 40 glorious years, until his Maha Samadhi. Guru and Master to hundreds of disciples, who made their way to him in pain and found solace in his presence. He performed innumerable miracles to help his committed disciples, remaining to this day a guiding light in their lives.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
            </div>
        </div>
