<div>Our Parents and Ancestors</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify">Conducted as Dharpanam pooja also known as Tithi for the blessings of our parents and ancestors at Srivanjiyum temple.People donate food to the hungry people in the hope that their ancestors will also be thus fed. People always realize the contributions of their forefathers, to their present life, and the cultural norms, traditions and values they set for us in order to make our lives better. According to the Vedic scriptures an individual is born with three debts. The debt to God is called ‘Dev-rin.’ The debt to the sages and saints is called ‘Rishi-rin.’ The third debt to one's parents and ancestors is called ‘Pitri-rin.’ These three debts are like three mortgages on one's life, but not liabilities. The third debt an individual is expected to pay during one's life is to one's parents and ancestors. Your ancestors are anxious to help you in all your endeavours and the departed souls are capable of doing so. However, they have one expectation from all and that is to perform acts of charity in their names and ancestors prayers known as tithi, shraadh or Shraadha or Dharpanam or anuual prayers and ceremonies during their annual visits to your homes in their subtle, invisible bodies.</div>
<div>&nbsp;</div>
<div class="text-justify">Srivanjiyum - VAANCHINATHAR Temple Tiruvaanchiyam is sixteen times more sacred than Varanasi. Yama built the temple and also stayed on here, as the vehicle for the Lord siva. Yama, the God of Death has an exclusive shrine for himself and is given preference in the daily worship. The Lord siva also told Yama that here a temple would be built for him and that devotees, who visit the Lord, should first offer prayers to Yama. The Moorthy-Lingam is supposed to be thousand times greater than the Holy Kasi. Sirardhamand Thila Homam, Ceremonies, Tithi, Dharpanam can be performed here for a person to whom no ceremonies had been performed earlier or there was a break in performing the ceremony. The presiding deity of this sacred temple Vanchinathar is a Swayambu Lingam and the oldest, the most ancient of the 64 Swayambhu Siva Lingams in the world. A prominent feature of this temple is that Yama, the God of Death has an exclusive shrine for himself and is given preference in the daily worship. A separate shrine for Bhairavar in a yogic posture is another rare feature of this temple. The unique feature of this temple is the shrine for both Rahu-Kethu which is carved out in one composite sculpture and when milk is poured over this Rahu-Kethu sculpture, it turns blue in colour. Worshiping at this shrine is said to bless devotees with marriage and progeny and cure nerve disorders. Worshiping Mahishasuramardhini with 108 lotus flowers during Rahu kalam is considered auspicious. A holy dip in Lakshmi Theertham is said to reunite a person with his separated family. A holy dip in Naga Theertham is said to liberate one, of all Naga Doshas. A holy dip in Chakra Theertham absolves one of Brahmahatti Dosham. Devotees are also cured of illness after a bath in the Gupta Ganga. According to the Puranas, a holy dip in the Gupta Ganga is equal to the ones in Varanasi, Rameswaram and the Maha Maham Tank at Kumbakonam. Lord Vinayakar on the banks of the Gupta Ganga is to be worshipped first, before taking the holy dip. According to legend, Yama, the God of Death, was worried about him and the consequences of taking away so many lives and wanted to atone for this act. Brahma allayed Yama’s fears and asked him to meditate on Lord Shiva for answer. Yama went to Gandhaaranyam, the fragrant forest and perform his penance. Sure enough, Lord Shiva appeared before Yama and asked him to built a temple. Yama built the temple and also stayed on here, as the vehicle for the Lord. The Lord also told Yama that a temple would be built for him and that devotees, who visit the Lord, should first offer prayers to Yama. A dip in the Gupta Ganga Tank is supposed to be a blessing and absolve one, of all sins and rebirths. The Moorthy-Lingam is supposed to be thousand times greater than the Holy Kasi. Here, even a death does not impact the routine Poojas, conducted in the temple. Normally, if there is a death in the village, the temple remains closed until the last rites are completed and not the case in this holy place of SRIVANJIYUM.</div>
